iLarge images can severely impact webpage loading speed. If your server		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iis in Hong Kong, Singapore, or China Telecom, and it's a		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ismall-bandwidth machine like 1M or 2M, then your loading speed is		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idefinitely not going to be good. Therefore, we need to compress		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iimages.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iCompressing images includes several methods:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Remove photo metadata, such as EXIF in JPEGs. This records camera		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iinformation and is completely useless when displayed on a webpage.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Reduce the number of colors, mainly for PNG's indexed colors. Since		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isome colors are indistinguishable to the human eye, it's better to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
imerge them into one color to reduce the image size.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Reduce resolution. This doesn't mean reducing the number of pixels,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibut rather the dots per inch (DPI), such as 72 dpi or 300 dpi. Regular		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
imonitors are 72 dpi, so higher values are useless and can be stripped.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iNote: This doesn't consider Retina displays. For Retina, simply		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
imultiply the image width and height by 0.5, and the problem is solved.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThere are many online tools and local tools for this. However, on Mac,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe most powerful one is ImageOptim. It's a combination of multiple		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itools that can compress images layer by layer to achieve maximum		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icompression, with (almost) no visible difference to the naked eye.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
